{"cursor":"26258","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"In mechanics, a 'constraint algorithm' is a method for satisfying constraints\nfor bodies that obey Newton's equations of motion. There are three basic\napproaches to satisfying such constraints: choosing novel unconstrained\ncoordinates (\"internal coordinates\"), introducing explicit constraint forces,\nand minimizing constraint forces implicitly by the technique of Lagrange\nmultipliers or projection methods.\n\nConstraint algorithms are often applied to molecular dynamics simulations.\nAlthough such simulations are sometimes carried out in internal coordinates that\nautomatically satisfy the bond-length and bond-angle constraints, they may also\nbe carried out with explicit or implicit constraint forces for the bond lengths\nand bond angles. Explicit constraint forces typically shorten the time-step\nsignificantly, making the simulation less efficient computationally; in other\nwords, more computer power is required to compute a trajectory of a given\nlength. Therefore, internal coordinates and implicit-force constraint solvers\nare generally preferred.\n","linknr":330,"url":"Constraint_algorithm","recorded":1362670962,"links":11,"instances":["geometric"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Molecular dynamics","Computational chemistry","Molecular physics","Computational physics","Numerical differential equations"],"headings":["Mathematical background","Internal coordinate methods","Lagrange multiplier-based methods","Hybrid methods","See also","References and footnotes"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/3/2/7329d2f70b601c1923f7602f67e4b90d.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/1/1/611e64dc239fef60a217ed76ad83e7bf.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/5/50/SHAKE.png/200px-SHAKE.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/c/4/4c4d0cef952cb198e0b60f2180932aa5.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/0/7/407e86544151c2e2d249d7054e7be